abstract: A showman who helped put “The Sound of Music” on television, “Chicago” on movie screens and “How to Succeed in Business” back on Broadway.
snippet: A showman who helped put “The Sound of Music” on television, “Chicago” on movie screens and “How to Succeed in Business” back on Broadway.
lead_paragraph: Craig Zadan, an ebullient showman who helped engineer a revival of Broadway musicals on television with live NBC broadcasts of “The Sound of Music,” “Peter Pan,” “Hairspray” and “The Wiz,” died on Tuesday at his home Los Angeles. He was 69.

abstract: The state tax department issued the subpoena after Mr. Cohen’s lawyer suggested his client might have information that could be useful to the investigation into President Trump’s charity.
snippet: The state tax department issued the subpoena after Mr. Cohen’s lawyer suggested his client might have information that could be useful to the investigation into President Trump’s charity.
lead_paragraph: Investigators in New York issued a subpoena to Michael D. Cohen, President Trump’s former fixer and lawyer, for documents related to the Donald J. Trump Foundation on Wednesday, an escalation of the Cuomo administration’s investigation into whether the president’s charity violated tax laws.

abstract: A new online tool pinpoints more than 7,000 major construction projects across New York City — part of an effort by the buildings department to make its data more accessible to the public.
snippet: A new online tool pinpoints more than 7,000 major construction projects across New York City — part of an effort by the buildings department to make its data more accessible to the public.
lead_paragraph: Just walk down any street these days for a New York experience as authentic — and unavoidable — as gridlock and dollar pizza: construction.

headline_main: A Real-Time Map Tracks the Building Frenzy That’s Transforming New York
headline_print_headline: Tracking the Building Frenzy Transforming the City

abstract: Andrea Yañes makes her New York Times Crossword debut, ably assisted by John Lieb.
snippet: Andrea Yañes makes her New York Times Crossword debut, ably assisted by John Lieb.
lead_paragraph: TUESDAY PUZZLE — My mother didn’t come up with it, but her one memorable piece of advice to me — other than the bit about clean underwear — was, “The one thing you can count on to stay the same is that everything changes.” Even this Bronx version of “Plus ça change, plus c’est la même chose” is a French-to-English translation of the same theme, so I guess she was right. Thanks, Mom.

abstract: A history of mistrust between the police in Chicago and the black community has led Steven Rosenthal’s family to raise questions about the circumstances of the young high school student’s death.
snippet: A history of mistrust between the police in Chicago and the black community has led Steven Rosenthal’s family to raise questions about the circumstances of the young high school student’s death.
lead_paragraph: When Chicago police officers found a 15-year-old they had been pursuing with a fatal gunshot wound to the head, they were quick to explain what had happened.

abstract: Three years ago, Parma’s soccer team had gone bankrupt and ceased to exist. On Sunday it makes its triumphant return to Italy’s Serie A.
snippet: Three years ago, Parma’s soccer team had gone bankrupt and ceased to exist. On Sunday it makes its triumphant return to Italy’s Serie A.
lead_paragraph: PARMA, Italy — Eight trophies are lined up along the back wall of the museum at Parma’s Stadio Ennio Tardini. Each one is polished to perfection, placed on a plinth and bathed in a soft spotlight, picking out the glint of silver and the gleam of gold. The effect is one of deep reverence, an almost holy glow.

abstract: Turks are handling the economic crisis with ambivalence and humor.

lead_paragraph: ISTANBUL — On Aug. 11, I was at a friend’s wedding at CerModern, a contemporary art museum in Ankara. Gold coins are the preferred wedding present in Turkey. The guests seemed subdued, but they did show up with gold coins in their clutches and pockets. Heated conversations around the price of gold filled the museum courtyard.
